Enum AminoAcid

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<AminoAcid>
      • AminoAcid
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<AminoAcid>

    public enum AminoAcid
extends java.lang.Enum<AminoAcid>
    Represents the standard amino acids with different categories for cis and trans proline. Backbone-dependent rotamer data is read from the Dunbrack library. We use traditional rotamers for amino acids containing all sp3-sp3 bonds in their sidechains. That is, we use ordered tuples (X1, X2, ..., Xn) to represent the backbone torsion angles, where n is the number of sidechain torsions. (OHs are not counted in the number of torsions. We use a combination of an ordered tuple and a DiscreteProbabilityDistribution to represent the non-rotameric amino acids. These amino acids contain an sp3-sp2 torsion at the end (e.g., phenylalanine). That is, we use an ordered tuple (X1, X2, ..., Xn-1) to represent the standard rotamer part of the sidechain and then a probability distribution to represent the terminal torsion. Some amino acids do not contain any rotable bonds (e.g. glycine) and therefore do not have associated library data.
